In principle, I agree, However…<br>
<br>
Space is expensive, not so much because the demanding nature of the technology (which it undoubtedly is) but because of the lack of mass production techniques.<br>
<br>
The triumph of 20th century industrial ingenuity is the ability to manufacture fantastically complex and sophisticated pieces of equipment for CENTS per unit or even less!<br>
<br>
I would not be surprised if there is more processing power in a high end PC graphics card than there was on the entire planet in 1969, and its yours for $200! (At the factory gate it is probably less than $20!).<br>
<br>
Why does the military have $1000 toilet seats? ‘Cos they are hand made, one at a time!<br>
<br>
Yesterday I was visiting a customer at his place of work. He is a “Metal basher”, He was making parts for Eurofighter, The part in question was a small section of tapered channel (a bit like a section of car bumper/fender) about 18” long. If you bought it as a Ford bodywork part it would probably cost $5!<br>
<br>
Because this is a Eurofighter part and hand made (also crack tested etc), he can only make 3 to 4 a week, the cost at the factory gate is probably not less than $2500 each.<br>
<br>
I found the following article intriguing, (particularly the astonishingly low marginal production cost on 5000+), Perhaps the author is correct and that this is the way to go, perhaps this is the best way to use public money to kickstart private investment..<br>
