Ok. I'm a little concerned that this calls for a number of years in which the US will have no manned space capability whatsoever. As John very rightly pointed out, this new orbital spaceplane may never fly. In fact I would be just as surprised as him if it actually worked. At the very least its going to cost 10 times the original projected estimates and take two to three times as long to build. Those are conservative and somewhat optimistic multiples. Just look up &quot;X-33&quot; or &quot;NASA Spaceplane&quot; and check for yourself. Meanwhile the US will have no birds and no edge. China will be halfway to Mars before the US gets its act together assuming it ever does. Such a fall might be hard to recover from. Russia will be happy to accept contracts for satellite repairs while this is going on. Golden Goose II greedily consumes countless billions of dollars and Russia leisurely takes over the manned space industry. Don't forget that Russians aren't opposed to profit making either. Without US competition they only have to contend with the ESA and a few other minor players. I guess that might prove a good thing. Give the underdogs a boost maybe. The US on the other hand may end up like Britain. A has been. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#6F6F6F>- </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace>NuclearSpace Message Board</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1>Open Forum</a> <font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><a href="http://www.nuclearspace.com">NuclearSpace Home Page</a><font color=#6F6F6F> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.3u<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  